    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="768"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d768">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51 Yunnan/26</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1366</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-24">July 24,
                            1937</date>.<lb/>[Received October 4.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to my despatch No. 1304
                    of June 30, 1937,<note n="88" xml:id="d768fn88">Not printed.</note> in regard to
                    the desire for an American loan to finance the proposed <pb facs="0623" n="615"
                        xml:id="pg_615"/> Chengtu–Yunnanfu Railway, and in this connection to
                    enclose a copy of despatch No. 269, July 10, 1937, from the Consul at
                        Yunnanfu<note n="88a" xml:id="d768fn88a">Not printed.</note> in which he
                    states that Mr. Hu Tao-wen, the Chinese official who has discussed the matter
                    with him previously, again called at the Consulate and made a plea for favorable
                    consideration of the desired loan. Mr. Penfield points out that the authorities
                    of both Yunnan and Szechuan are anxious to obtain this loan, that the
                    authorities desire neither British nor French capital to be employed, and that
                    if the Nanking authorities are in favor of it, (as Mr. Hu maintains is the case)
                    the project might be regarded as a favorable opportunity for the investment of
                    American capital and for the sale of American railway equipment.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Ambassador:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Frank P. Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Counselor of Embassy</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
